1: Damaging to the Enemy<br>
2: If not damaging, does it match a sideline?<br>
3: Based on the manipulation of Fire, Ice, Force or Lighting<br>
4: Should exist in game lore as reasonable spells that a wizard would develop--this is the easiest part.<br>
5: Be balanced for the game and against the abilities of the other classes.--This is the hard one.<br>
<br>
As a further point, any highly useful or core grouping ability should be spread out among no less than 3 classes as the game stands right now.  This is due to the number of classes in game as opposed to the number of group slots available.  The lack of this foresight on sony's part is what creates the phenomenom of the 'Holy Trininy'.  <br>
<br>
So, let's take for example a Poison based Nuke, one of your suggestions that you'd thought I'd find reasonable.<br>
<br>
1. Damaging to the enemy- Yep<br>
2. Based on Fire/ice/magic- no<br>
3. Explained?- yes, it's only for those who worship cazic.<br>
4. Balanced?- I'd say no, and don't do it, unless as a design decision similar quest spells were given to all classes.  This would then erupt in a huge war over who has better quest spells ect... and be too much bother to actually do.  Balance is the real deciding factor here.<br>
<br>
Now my ideas-<br>
Damage Adding Debuff<br>
1. Damaging- Yep<br>
2. should be based on Ice imho<br>
3. effect is ice shards being driven further into the victim<br>
4. Balanced?-- I'd say yes.  It meets a need in the game, the issue of wizard group utility.  It's a damaging utility, so wizards are in their primary role. It does not help wizards solo overmuch, as the efficency of such a spell goes down with the fewer participants in the battle.  Does it infringe on other class's role?  Clerics do get a similar spell, but it's hardly their primary focus.<br>
<br>
Inner Fire<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(just realized this is a level 1 shaman buff, it needs a name change)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
1. Not damaging<br>
2. Does match a sideline- that of instant mana<br>
3. Based on the manipulation of magic.<br>
4. Sets up a much larger harvest effect, but easily interupted.<br>
5. Balanced? I'd say so.  Again, it meets a need in the game, that of alleviating extreme enforced downtime- Melee do not suffer this same lack as instant healing spells are found on several classes. Wizards already get a similar effect that is self only, and extremly limited- as such this line should be shared as it's a sideline, and mana regen lies as a specialty of other classes--those classes do not have the need for group utility however, nor do they specialize in instant effects.  No one else recieves an effect like this, closest spells are the subversion line of Necromancers, Mod Rods, Cannibalize, and Harvest-- all of which differ not only by the magnitude of the mana gain, but also in the respect that they are usefull in combat.  It also would probably be necessary to disable this effect in raid areas, as getting out of combat in a 60 player vs. 1 mob fight is pretty easy.  If it's not disabled, it needs an effect to attract an aggroed mobs attention--disabling would be better due to aggro list size.<br>
<br>
Proc Buff<br>
1. Damages enemy<br>
2. Fire/Ice/Magic of course<br>
3. Firey aura that occasionally burns the creature-basically an offensively used damage sheild<br>
4.Balanced?  For Wizards, perhaps not.  A line like this rightfully belongs to Necromancers, who get the first proc buff in the game, and Enchanters, as the effect lends itself more to enchanting weapons-- enchanters do not need more group utility however.  The reverse damage sheild effect is probably better suited for the same purpose this spell would serve in a wizards arsenal.  Also, buffs are not a wizards area.  In short, it would not hurt, but alternatives are better.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Mine is, even fun spells should actually fit the class and even fun spells should be balanced appropriately<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I agree that spells should fit the class, and that even fun spells should be appropriatly balanced.<br>
<br>
Where we seem to disagree is on what constitues balance for a purely fun spell.  Under what circumstances is a spell like Voice Graft balanced?  Given the effect, I'd say its appropriate to anyone that controls a humanoid type NPC.  Thus, Enchanters could make charm victims say anything they wanted too, Necromancers can speak through the dead, and Wizards could use their familiar as a messenger.  Pre-Luclin, mage pets were only very remotely humanoid, and I'd rule it out-- with the new graphics however, I'd say they are fair recipents too.  Shadowknights get the effect through a weapon, which is appropriate given their far lesser mastery of the dead.<br>
<br>
On long lasting eye type scouting spells, there may actually be a balance issue.  It has uses with Eye of Zomm, It could be used to check on spawns, it can be used to remotely aggro creatures with pets which if they don't have social aggro will be single pulled.  However, do these issues make it Overpowered, or just useful.  I vote useful, as the existing eye spells can be used for these too, and thoughtful zone design can cancel the one factor that would make it dangerous--that of remote aggroing.  It would actually enhance the usefulness of COH without increasing the current problems with the spell.  You can check spawns with a ranger, camped non aggro toon, or just bugging the current eyes if your bored, depending on zone.  You can just make any mob that should not be coming alone have guards that aggro with it.  <br>
<br>
If there's another issue with Eye spells, I can't think of it.  I see a long lasting version as useful, fun utility.  If being able to look around has a more serious issue associated with it-- for instance content that gives you limited time to solve a puzzle in an area or else mobs aggro-- then perhaps it should be downchecked, but otherwise it seems fine, balanced and reasonable to me.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And both of those apply even more to spells that have more functions inside the game. You view this as a negative stance, but it isn't. It just doesn't match your idea of fun, but you don't seem to like much difference in classes either.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
I agree, balance on spells that actually do effect the core gameplay need very close scrutiny.  What I found negative was the apparent attitude that if the class did not currently have the ability, then it does not belong on the class.  How any new effects can be given out with that viewpoint I don't know, and explains why every suggestion is met with condecending scorn.<br>
<br>
What ideas you may have that don't match my idea of fun I wouldn't know.  So far you have shown no positive input on the thread whatsoever, only came in to shoot down and deride those who did have suggestions.  Negative is as Negative does, if it looks like a duck, where there's smoke...   I just call it like I see it.  That's why I have repeated asked for reasons things are unbalanced, and suggestions from you on what you feel would be.  I'll take the bad with the good, but getting some good would be...fun. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I believe I have amply demonstrated that I do like distinct classes.  That distiction is not found in the game mechanics however, but in the focus of the class.  <br>
<br>
One class can nuke with the elements, another the power of their god--and that's fine.  The supporting elements will come in with resist rates/types, reletive size of the nukes, and secondary abilities of the class. Both nuke, and the effect is mechanicly the same, but the flavor is different.<br>
<br>
This is born out better with the examples of the games 3 main tank classes. Warriors survive by sheer hitpoints, Shadowknights augment their hitpoints with taps, Paladins augment their hitpoints by stuning and healing.  In xp situations, the classes are for the most part interchangeable, with an edge going to the hybrids due to spell aggro.  On those that do large amounts of damage quickly, warriors are superior, as the augmentation abilities of the other 2 are not as useful against burst damage.  Each has a niche which in theory makes them optimum in different circumstances-- though poor game design in many cases reduces the usefulness of the differences, as mobs, especially common mobs, are not that different from eachother. <p><br>
